3
00:00:20,888 --> 00:00:23,021
                     ♪♪         

4
00:00:23,023 --> 00:00:25,391
            narrator:           
  today, on "how it's made"...  

5
00:00:25,393 --> 00:00:34,966
                     ♪♪         

6
00:00:34,968 --> 00:00:44,243
                     ♪♪         

7
00:00:44,245 --> 00:00:53,685
                     ♪♪         

8
00:00:53,687 --> 00:00:55,554
     somewhere back in time,    

9
00:00:55,556 --> 00:00:58,290
 somebody was blowing on a fire 
        to get it started       

10
00:00:58,292 --> 00:01:00,125
      and wondered if there     
       were a way to do it      

11
00:01:00,127 --> 00:01:02,127
    without hyperventilating.   

12
00:01:02,129 --> 00:01:04,363
         a lot of people        
     must have had this idea    

13
00:01:04,365 --> 00:01:05,931
        because different       
        kinds of bellows        

14
00:01:05,933 --> 00:01:10,436
 can be found across the ancient
    world from egypt to asia.   

15
00:01:13,641 --> 00:01:15,975
     in the auvergne region     
       of central france,       

16
00:01:15,977 --> 00:01:18,143
        this manufacturer       
        has been building       

17
00:01:18,145 --> 00:01:21,446
    classic fireplace bellows   
           since 1895           

18
00:01:21,448 --> 00:01:26,051
  using high-quality beechwood  
   and leather sourced nearby.  

19
00:01:26,053 --> 00:01:28,253
        an artisan starts       
     by selecting a template    

20
00:01:28,255 --> 00:01:30,823
          from a range          
      of sizes and shapes.      

21
00:01:30,825 --> 00:01:33,292
      he traces an outline      
       on a piece of wood.      

22
00:01:35,462 --> 00:01:38,864
    he uses a band saw to cut   
 the rough outline of the shape 

23
00:01:38,866 --> 00:01:40,699
  to prepare for the next step. 

24
00:01:43,337 --> 00:01:46,872
 a craftsman then places a stack
    of three rough-cut shapes   

25
00:01:46,874 --> 00:01:51,844
  on top of a master prototype  
 and clamps the stack in place. 

26
00:01:51,846 --> 00:01:55,214
    a large bearing slides up   
  against the master prototype  

27
00:01:55,216 --> 00:01:56,448
      and, by following it,     

28
00:01:56,450 --> 00:01:58,150
      guides a specialized      
          cutting tool          

29
00:01:58,152 --> 00:02:01,820
      around the perimeter      
          of the stack.         

30
00:02:01,822 --> 00:02:03,188
      the operation quickly     

31
00:02:03,190 --> 00:02:05,958
      and precisely reduces     
    the three pieces of wood    

32
00:02:05,960 --> 00:02:08,460
     to exactly the required    
           dimensions.          

33
00:02:08,462 --> 00:02:13,666
                     ♪♪         

34
00:02:13,668 --> 00:02:15,768
  this purpose-built mechanism  
           undertakes           

35
00:02:15,770 --> 00:02:18,237
     a three-step operation.    

36
00:02:18,239 --> 00:02:20,839
     a drill pierces a hole     
        in the narrow end       

37
00:02:20,841 --> 00:02:25,210
   while a second drill opens   
     three holes underneath.    

38
00:02:25,212 --> 00:02:27,813
     a circular saw quickly     
         slices partway         

39
00:02:27,815 --> 00:02:31,650
 through the neck of the piece. 

40
00:02:31,652 --> 00:02:34,019
      a craftsman then uses     
          a rotary tool         

41
00:02:34,021 --> 00:02:36,955
   to easily cut a decorative   
  pattern of concentric circles 

42
00:02:36,957 --> 00:02:38,724
   into one side of the wood.   

43
00:02:41,695 --> 00:02:44,763
   a cutting blade positioned   
  at precisely the right height 

44
00:02:44,765 --> 00:02:48,233
   allows an artisan to slice   
    a beveled groove partway    

45
00:02:48,235 --> 00:02:51,570
around the perimeter of the wood
     to the required depth.     

46
00:02:55,242 --> 00:02:57,909
        a craftsman uses        
       a powerful band saw      

47
00:02:57,911 --> 00:03:00,746
   to divide the wood in half   
      along the groove line     

48
00:03:00,748 --> 00:03:03,448
    all the way up to the cut   
        across the neck.        

49
00:03:03,450 --> 00:03:09,421
                     ♪♪         

50
00:03:09,423 --> 00:03:13,025
  the wooden components are now 
 ready for the finished process.

51
00:03:15,563 --> 00:03:18,830
 an artisan dunks the components
        in a tub of stain       

52
00:03:18,832 --> 00:03:21,700
         and places them        
       on a shelf to dry.       

53
00:03:21,702 --> 00:03:24,436
       she keeps each pair      
     of components together     

54
00:03:24,438 --> 00:03:26,438
      while separating them     
       slightly to ensure       

55
00:03:26,440 --> 00:03:28,907
   they don't stick together.   

56
00:03:31,478 --> 00:03:33,378
    once the stain has dried,   

57
00:03:33,380 --> 00:03:36,114
   the artisan buffs the outer  
   surfaces of the components   

58
00:03:36,116 --> 00:03:38,951
       on a buffing wheel       
    to make the wood smooth.    

59
00:03:43,390 --> 00:03:46,491
  she then carefully positions  
    the components on a table   

60
00:03:46,493 --> 00:03:49,928
 and sprays them thoroughly with
 a protective layer of varnish. 

61
00:03:53,601 --> 00:03:55,401
   once the varnish has cured,  

62
00:03:55,403 --> 00:03:57,736
         a craftsperson         
       can begin assembly       

63
00:03:57,738 --> 00:04:00,606
      by creating the valve     
  that covers the intake hole.  

64
00:04:03,244 --> 00:04:05,644
     she installs a rounded     
         length of wire,        

65
00:04:05,646 --> 00:04:08,980
    stapling it in such a way   
   as to create enough tension  

66
00:04:08,982 --> 00:04:11,316
for the wire to act as a spring.

67
00:04:11,318 --> 00:04:14,519
       this step completes      
  the interior of the bellows.  

68
00:04:14,521 --> 00:04:19,658
                     ♪♪         

69
00:04:19,660 --> 00:04:24,596
an artisan can now bring the two
 halves of the bellows together.

70
00:04:24,598 --> 00:04:27,132
     she starts by wrapping     
         a precut piece         

71
00:04:27,134 --> 00:04:30,468
   of locally sourced sheep's   
    leather around one handle   

72
00:04:30,470 --> 00:04:35,274
    and attaching the leather   
   in place with small nails.   

73
00:04:35,276 --> 00:04:38,877
 carefully hammering a series of
 closely-spaced upholstery tacks

74
00:04:38,879 --> 00:04:40,478
      at regular intervals      

75
00:04:40,480 --> 00:04:42,781
       secures the leather      
      to the perimeter edge     

76
00:04:42,783 --> 00:04:44,817
   of one half of the bellows.  

77
00:04:48,288 --> 00:04:50,889
       the artisan can now      
     attach the second half     

78
00:04:50,891 --> 00:04:55,394
  by repeating the operation on 
 the other side of the leather. 

79
00:04:55,396 --> 00:04:58,029
 adding a thin strip of leather 
       along the tack line      

80
00:04:58,031 --> 00:05:00,532
        will help prevent       
     any ripping or tearing.    

81
00:05:00,534 --> 00:05:06,304
                     ♪♪         

82
00:05:06,306 --> 00:05:09,908
  the artisan uses a section of 
precut leather to form the hinge

83
00:05:09,910 --> 00:05:13,779
    necessary for the proper    
   functioning of the bellows.  

84
00:05:13,781 --> 00:05:17,716
  the size, position, and tack  
   pattern must all be precise  

85
00:05:17,718 --> 00:05:21,653
  in order for the tool to open 
 and close smoothly and easily. 

86
00:05:21,655 --> 00:05:28,360
                     ♪♪         

87
00:05:28,362 --> 00:05:33,165
      the artisan trims off     
 any excess lengths of leather. 

88
00:05:33,167 --> 00:05:37,202
            finally,            
    she installs the nozzle.    

89
00:05:37,204 --> 00:05:40,205
    making a dent with a tool   
called a punch prepares the site

90
00:05:40,207 --> 00:05:44,576
    for a nail which secures    
      the nozzle in place.      

91
00:05:44,578 --> 00:05:48,247
      the completed bellows     
       function perfectly.      

92
00:05:48,249 --> 00:05:51,850
this simple, finely crafted tool
     is built to help start     

93
00:05:51,852 --> 00:05:54,620
  warm fires for years to come. 

94
00:06:05,765 --> 00:06:11,036
                     ♪♪         

95
00:06:11,038 --> 00:06:14,372
     narrator: calissons are    
   a traditional french candy   

96
00:06:14,374 --> 00:06:17,776
 made of almonds, candied melon,
         and orange peel        

97
00:06:17,778 --> 00:06:22,047
   topped with a thin layer of  
  hard, typically white, icing. 

98
00:06:22,049 --> 00:06:25,851
   calissons are the specialty  
 of the city of aix-en-provence 

99
00:06:25,853 --> 00:06:28,453
     in the provence region     
       of southern france.      

100
00:06:31,325 --> 00:06:35,060
   the calisson was created in  
 france in the mid-15th century 

101
00:06:35,062 --> 00:06:37,830
     in honor of the wedding    
      of king rene of anjou     

102
00:06:37,832 --> 00:06:39,831
   and queen jeanne of laval.   

103
00:06:39,833 --> 00:06:42,768
      the confection became     
   the specialty of provence,   

104
00:06:42,770 --> 00:06:47,439
  the region of southern france 
 known for its almond orchards. 

105
00:06:47,441 --> 00:06:50,542
    inside the greenish hull    
        is a hard shell.        

106
00:06:50,544 --> 00:06:53,712
      inside that shell is      
     the edible almond seed.    

107
00:06:53,714 --> 00:06:57,115
    the almonds arrive at the   
 workshop dried for conservation

108
00:06:57,117 --> 00:06:59,351
  and their brown skin removed. 

109
00:06:59,353 --> 00:07:02,487
the first step in the production
   is to rehydrate the almonds  

110
00:07:02,489 --> 00:07:04,656
 with steam for about 10 minutes

111
00:07:04,658 --> 00:07:07,158
       so that they can be      
      worked into a paste.      

112
00:07:07,160 --> 00:07:09,094
        once the almonds'       
        moisture content        

113
00:07:09,096 --> 00:07:11,462
    is increased by 2 to 4%,    

114
00:07:11,464 --> 00:07:14,132
      the almonds pass over     
       a vibrating screen       

115
00:07:14,134 --> 00:07:17,903
  to drain any water resulting  
    from steam condensation.    

116
00:07:17,905 --> 00:07:21,739
    meanwhile, this cauldron    
   heats up liquid beet sugar.  

117
00:07:21,741 --> 00:07:25,210
  france is one of the world's  
  largest sugar beet producers, 

118
00:07:25,212 --> 00:07:30,348
   so high-quality beet sugar   
      is readily available.     

119
00:07:30,350 --> 00:07:33,552
  workers transfer the hydrated 
      almonds to a grinder      

120
00:07:33,554 --> 00:07:39,224
    and add candied fruit --    
  95% melon and 5% orange peel. 

121
00:07:39,226 --> 00:07:44,095
 this flavor is the 500-year-old
       traditional recipe.      

122
00:07:44,097 --> 00:07:46,931
  workers grind the ingredients 
      for about 10 minutes      

123
00:07:46,933 --> 00:07:51,469
 until everything is thoroughly 
  blended into a coarse paste.  

124
00:07:51,471 --> 00:07:53,872
         the paste drops        
      onto a conveyor belt,     

125
00:07:53,874 --> 00:07:55,807
       which transfers it       
      to a kneading machine     

126
00:07:55,809 --> 00:07:58,977
     into which workers add     
    the hot liquid beet sugar   

127
00:07:58,979 --> 00:08:03,014
     and natural almond oil     
    made from bitter almonds.   

128
00:08:03,016 --> 00:08:04,883
 kneading blends the ingredients

129
00:08:04,885 --> 00:08:08,553
    and smoothes the texture    
          of the paste.         

130
00:08:08,555 --> 00:08:11,056
         a worker boxes         
       the calisson paste       

131
00:08:11,058 --> 00:08:13,257
and sets it aside for three days

132
00:08:13,259 --> 00:08:17,762
        to let the sugar        
      mature and stabilize.     

133
00:08:17,764 --> 00:08:20,265
    calissons are topped with   
      an ever-so-thin layer     

134
00:08:20,267 --> 00:08:22,467
         of royal icing.        

135
00:08:22,469 --> 00:08:27,105
      unlike creamy icings,     
royal icing is as hard as a rock

136
00:08:27,107 --> 00:08:30,208
      to make it, a worker      
      combines icing sugar      

137
00:08:30,210 --> 00:08:34,479
     and whipped egg whites     
   passed through a strainer.   

138
00:08:34,481 --> 00:08:36,514
  a mixer beats the ingredients 

139
00:08:36,516 --> 00:08:38,650
        until the mixture       
      is thick and smooth,      

140
00:08:38,652 --> 00:08:41,286
      which typically takes     
        about 10 minutes.       

141
00:08:41,288 --> 00:08:50,662
                     ♪♪         

142
00:08:50,664 --> 00:08:55,466
      after 3 days of rest,     
the paste is ready to be worked.

143
00:08:55,468 --> 00:08:59,938
   shaping and decorating the   
 calissons is a specialized task

144
00:08:59,940 --> 00:09:02,007
       entrusted to these       
      experienced artisans      

145
00:09:02,009 --> 00:09:04,842
     called "calissonaires."    

146
00:09:04,844 --> 00:09:08,012
    first, they place slices    
       of paste in a press      

147
00:09:08,014 --> 00:09:11,583
   and load a mold underneath.  

148
00:09:11,585 --> 00:09:15,120
they cover the mold with a wafer
-thin sheet of unleavened bread.

149
00:09:17,590 --> 00:09:20,792
then, the press piston descends,
       forcing the paste,       

150
00:09:20,794 --> 00:09:22,226
with the bread layer underneath,

151
00:09:22,228 --> 00:09:24,529
         into the mold.         

152
00:09:24,531 --> 00:09:27,899
 they skim off the excess paste,

153
00:09:27,901 --> 00:09:30,735
      then fold the stencil     
          over the mold         

154
00:09:30,737 --> 00:09:32,904
       and apply the layer      
         of royal icing.        

155
00:09:35,675 --> 00:09:38,110
    they lift off the stencil   
      and push the buttons      

156
00:09:38,112 --> 00:09:41,246
which activate the mold pistons.

157
00:09:41,248 --> 00:09:43,849
       each piston pierces      
     the base of a calisson     

158
00:09:43,851 --> 00:09:45,617
  and lifts it out of the mold. 

159
00:09:48,021 --> 00:09:50,822
      finally, they remove      
    the calissons with combs    

160
00:09:50,824 --> 00:09:52,958
         designed to fit        
       around the pistons.      

161
00:09:55,396 --> 00:09:57,662
        a 10-minute trip        
      through a tunnel oven     

162
00:09:57,664 --> 00:10:00,065
     set at low temperature     
      bakes the royal icing     

163
00:10:00,067 --> 00:10:03,901
   to a hard and shiny state.   

164
00:10:03,903 --> 00:10:06,270
   cameras record the position  
        of the calissons        

165
00:10:06,272 --> 00:10:07,872
     as they exit the oven,     

166
00:10:07,874 --> 00:10:11,376
      guiding a robotic arm     
    to pick up 160 per minute   

167
00:10:11,378 --> 00:10:14,579
and place them in plastic trays.

168
00:10:14,581 --> 00:10:17,382
the next machine seals each tray
        with plastic film       

169
00:10:17,384 --> 00:10:19,984
     to preserve freshness.     

170
00:10:19,986 --> 00:10:23,955
 there's also a gift box format 
  for which a worker hand-fills 

171
00:10:23,957 --> 00:10:25,590
          plastic trays         

172
00:10:25,592 --> 00:10:29,261
         designed to fit        
   lozenge-shaped metal boxes.  

173
00:10:29,263 --> 00:10:32,764
   these traditional calissons  
 contain a candied fruit content

174
00:10:32,766 --> 00:10:36,534
        of at least 30%,        
    the melon being a variety   

175
00:10:36,536 --> 00:10:38,837
           cultivated           
   in the region of provence.   

176
00:10:42,542 --> 00:10:45,777
 however, if your taste buds are
  the type that buck tradition, 

177
00:10:45,779 --> 00:10:47,679
             today,             
 you can enjoy a wide selection 

178
00:10:47,681 --> 00:10:49,947
  of other fashionable flavors  

179
00:10:49,949 --> 00:10:52,117
       such as clementine       
         and cocoa bean         

180
00:10:52,119 --> 00:10:54,853
          or raspberry          
      and matcha green tea.     

181
00:11:03,130 --> 00:11:08,233
                     ♪♪         

182
00:11:08,235 --> 00:11:11,036
  narrator: this new generation 
     of personal watercraft     

183
00:11:11,038 --> 00:11:13,104
is something entirely different.

184
00:11:13,106 --> 00:11:15,606
          it does more          
     than skim the surface.     

185
00:11:15,608 --> 00:11:19,244
this watercraft dives underwater
    and can remain submerged    

186
00:11:19,246 --> 00:11:22,280
    at a depth of three feet    
   or more for up to a minute.  

187
00:11:22,282 --> 00:11:25,784
   it also leaps into the air   
    and rolls with the waves.   

188
00:11:29,189 --> 00:11:33,391
  this watercraft is painted to 
look like a vintage fighter jet,

189
00:11:33,393 --> 00:11:37,295
     and it rolls and dives     
     like one in the water.     

190
00:11:37,297 --> 00:11:41,098
   a worker sprays a gel coat   
 into a mold for the main body. 

191
00:11:41,100 --> 00:11:42,434
      this gel will become      

192
00:11:42,436 --> 00:11:46,304
      the shiny surface of      
 the completed fiberglass part. 

193
00:11:46,306 --> 00:11:48,273
 once the gel coat has hardened,

194
00:11:48,275 --> 00:11:51,509
    a worker brushes a vinyl    
      ester resin onto it.      

195
00:11:51,511 --> 00:11:55,213
       this resin is known      
    for its water resistance.   

196
00:11:55,215 --> 00:11:57,682
    he switches from a brush    
           to a roller          

197
00:11:57,684 --> 00:11:59,684
         as he generally        
        applies the resin       

198
00:11:59,686 --> 00:12:02,187
    to the hardened gel coat.   

199
00:12:02,189 --> 00:12:05,189
      the crew then drapes      
what's called chopped-strand mat

200
00:12:05,191 --> 00:12:06,457
         over the mold.         

201
00:12:06,459 --> 00:12:09,727
   this fabric is made of long  
     strands of fiberglass.     

202
00:12:09,729 --> 00:12:12,831
   the binder in it dissolves   
   on contact with the resin,   

203
00:12:12,833 --> 00:12:16,501
  causing the fabric to soften  
  to the contours of the mold.  

204
00:12:16,503 --> 00:12:18,936
         after trimming         
      the excess material,      

205
00:12:18,938 --> 00:12:23,041
  the crew completely saturates 
 the strand mat with more resin.

206
00:12:23,043 --> 00:12:27,078
      rolling it on firmly      
    gets rid of air bubbles.    

207
00:12:27,080 --> 00:12:29,146
    the top half of the main    
            body mold           

208
00:12:29,148 --> 00:12:31,149
  has been lined the same way.  

209
00:12:34,153 --> 00:12:35,587
   they now bolt a dorsal fin   

210
00:12:35,589 --> 00:12:38,823
        mold to the back        
  on the top half of the mold.  

211
00:12:43,797 --> 00:12:46,831
       the crew now joins       
   the two halves of the mold.  

212
00:12:50,403 --> 00:12:53,004
    as a crane lowers the top   
         to the bottom,         

213
00:12:53,006 --> 00:12:55,740
         workers ensure         
     they line up perfectly.    

214
00:12:55,742 --> 00:13:00,478
     and they lock these two    
 main molds together with bolts.

215
00:13:00,480 --> 00:13:02,280
     a worker enters through    
           the cockpit          

216
00:13:02,282 --> 00:13:04,548
 opening to roll on more resin. 

217
00:13:04,550 --> 00:13:10,655
                     ♪♪         

218
00:13:10,657 --> 00:13:12,524
    meanwhile, another member   
           of the crew          

219
00:13:12,526 --> 00:13:14,525
        pulls two sheets        
      of fiberglass fabric      

220
00:13:14,527 --> 00:13:16,561
     onto a cutting machine.    

221
00:13:16,563 --> 00:13:20,231
   the top fabric is a strong,  
    tightly woven fiberglass,   

222
00:13:20,233 --> 00:13:24,068
       and the bottom one       
   is the chopped-strand mat.   

223
00:13:24,070 --> 00:13:27,138
      automated blades cut      
the fiberglass to various shapes

224
00:13:27,140 --> 00:13:28,273
         and dimensions,        

225
00:13:28,275 --> 00:13:30,174
        each one designed       
      for a different part      

226
00:13:30,176 --> 00:13:34,212
   of the diving vessel mold.   

227
00:13:34,214 --> 00:13:36,347
     these large rectangles     
      will be used to mold      

228
00:13:36,349 --> 00:13:39,116
  the sides of the watercraft.  

229
00:13:39,118 --> 00:13:40,819
  after folding up the pieces,  

230
00:13:40,821 --> 00:13:44,222
   the worker hands them over   
  to the fiberglass technician. 

231
00:13:46,226 --> 00:13:49,394
 the technician has just an hour
     to apply the fiberglass    

232
00:13:49,396 --> 00:13:52,830
   before the recently applied  
     resin starts to harden.    

233
00:13:52,832 --> 00:13:54,565
    he builds up eight layers   

234
00:13:54,567 --> 00:13:59,304
    and completely saturates    
    each one with more resin.   

235
00:13:59,306 --> 00:14:02,974
  while the thicker fiberglass  
   material provides strength,  

236
00:14:02,976 --> 00:14:05,743
 the thinner chopped-strand mat 
          aids adhesion         

237
00:14:05,745 --> 00:14:10,348
      and helps the fabrics     
      conform to the mold.      

238
00:14:10,350 --> 00:14:17,022
  after a 3-hour cure, workers  
have a solid, seamless fuselage.

239
00:14:17,024 --> 00:14:19,890
  the crane lifts the fuselage  
         out of the mold        

240
00:14:19,892 --> 00:14:22,294
    and moves it onto a dolly   
       where it will stay       

241
00:14:22,296 --> 00:14:25,297
   while the team works on the  
 other parts of the watercraft. 

242
00:14:29,502 --> 00:14:32,937
      the cone-shaped front     
         bumper is next.        

243
00:14:32,939 --> 00:14:36,207
   the worker uses only three   
 layers of fiberglass to make it

244
00:14:36,209 --> 00:14:38,376
  because this bumper is meant  
           to collapse          

245
00:14:38,378 --> 00:14:41,112
  in the event of a collision.  

246
00:14:41,114 --> 00:14:43,314
        for that reason,        
     the part is also known     

247
00:14:43,316 --> 00:14:46,117
         as the vessel's        
        sacrificial nose.       

248
00:14:46,119 --> 00:14:51,055
                     ♪♪         

249
00:14:51,057 --> 00:14:52,424
       at another station,      

250
00:14:52,426 --> 00:14:55,693
        crew members line       
fin-shaped molds with fiberglass

251
00:14:55,695 --> 00:14:58,797
     and then pour liquefied    
    plastic into the cavity.    

252
00:14:58,799 --> 00:15:02,100
  once cured, the plastic will  
    anchor the top of a steel   

253
00:15:02,102 --> 00:15:03,901
     wing shaft in the fin.     

254
00:15:03,903 --> 00:15:06,170
   a worker presses the shaft   
       into the liquefied       

255
00:15:06,172 --> 00:15:07,639
      plastic with the end      

256
00:15:07,641 --> 00:15:10,508
    protruding from the fin.    

257
00:15:10,510 --> 00:15:13,177
         a second mold,         
   also lined with fiberglass   

258
00:15:13,179 --> 00:15:16,814
 and filled with a plastic core,
          goes on top.          

259
00:15:16,816 --> 00:15:21,085
   the team bolts it together   
  and leaves the part to cure.  

260
00:15:21,087 --> 00:15:23,421
    the fins will ultimately    
          be supported          

261
00:15:23,423 --> 00:15:25,089
    by a triangular scaffold    

262
00:15:25,091 --> 00:15:27,392
 made of aluminum square tubing.

263
00:15:27,394 --> 00:15:30,829
 the worker clamps the scaffold 
    framework to a worktable    

264
00:15:30,831 --> 00:15:34,098
   to stabilize the framework   
    as he welds it together.    

265
00:15:34,100 --> 00:15:37,868
   he then welds the scaffold   
       tower to the base.       

266
00:15:37,870 --> 00:15:40,538
   the worker drills holes for  
 the bushings that will be used 

267
00:15:40,540 --> 00:15:42,841
       to attach the fins       
        to the scaffold.        

268
00:15:46,279 --> 00:15:48,880
       stay tuned for more      
      as the team prepares      

269
00:15:48,882 --> 00:15:52,617
 this personal diving watercraft
     for its maiden voyage.     

270
00:16:05,799 --> 00:16:11,502
                     ♪♪         

271
00:16:11,504 --> 00:16:13,537
            narrator:           
 this personal watercraft leaps,

272
00:16:13,539 --> 00:16:16,173
     dives, and barrel-rolls    
         with the waves.        

273
00:16:16,175 --> 00:16:18,376
     but it doesn't capsize.    

274
00:16:18,378 --> 00:16:19,978
 it's been engineered to return 

275
00:16:19,980 --> 00:16:22,347
          to an upright         
     position in the water.     

276
00:16:22,349 --> 00:16:25,616
  and when it comes to the fun  
 factor, this diving watercraft 

277
00:16:25,618 --> 00:16:28,219
 leaves other recreational boats
          in its wake.          

278
00:16:32,225 --> 00:16:35,025
 to make the diving watercraft's
        passenger cabin,        

279
00:16:35,027 --> 00:16:37,328
   a worker sprays a gel coat   
           onto a form          

280
00:16:37,330 --> 00:16:40,064
 and covers it with fiberglass. 

281
00:16:40,066 --> 00:16:44,002
  a computer-driven router then 
carves into marine-grade plywood

282
00:16:44,004 --> 00:16:47,439
  to produce structural backing 
  for the sides of the cockpit. 

283
00:16:50,409 --> 00:16:53,711
a worker slathers adhesive putty
      onto the plywood part     

284
00:16:53,713 --> 00:16:56,714
    and applies more adhesive   
   to the fiberglass cockpit.   

285
00:16:59,453 --> 00:17:03,288
    he presses the plywood to   
 the glued areas of the cockpit 

286
00:17:03,290 --> 00:17:05,990
     and brushes resin onto     
    the front of the plywood.   

287
00:17:08,995 --> 00:17:11,496
    after cutting the cockpit   
         section in two,        

288
00:17:11,498 --> 00:17:15,266
    the crew glues the parts    
 to the inside of the fuselage. 

289
00:17:17,504 --> 00:17:20,304
      the fabricating team      
     applies adhesive putty     

290
00:17:20,306 --> 00:17:23,641
    to the cone-shaped bumper   
 known as the sacrificial nose. 

291
00:17:26,246 --> 00:17:29,581
  they slide it onto the front  
         of the fuselage        

292
00:17:29,583 --> 00:17:32,182
    and the screw the bumper    
      in place temporarily      

293
00:17:32,184 --> 00:17:33,918
    while the adhesive sets.    

294
00:17:37,089 --> 00:17:39,456
      another worker sands      
    all the fiberglass parts    

295
00:17:39,458 --> 00:17:43,060
        of the watercraft       
 to remove bumps and blemishes. 

296
00:17:43,062 --> 00:17:45,196
 this piece is the engine hatch.

297
00:17:47,200 --> 00:17:49,199
         the team bolts         
      the aluminum scaffold     

298
00:17:49,201 --> 00:17:51,002
  to the floor of the fuselage. 

299
00:17:51,004 --> 00:17:53,004
  this is a test fit to confirm 

300
00:17:53,006 --> 00:17:55,373
       that the dimensions      
       are exactly right.       

301
00:17:59,378 --> 00:18:02,580
 as they installed the scaffold,
   the used dummy wing shafts   

302
00:18:02,582 --> 00:18:05,983
    to correctly position it    
       within the vessel.       

303
00:18:05,985 --> 00:18:08,019
      they confirm that the     
      dimensions are right      

304
00:18:08,021 --> 00:18:12,857
and that the scaffold sits plumb
 to the base of the watercraft. 

305
00:18:12,859 --> 00:18:14,726
      the next team inserts     
         the hatch frame        

306
00:18:14,728 --> 00:18:17,295
 and the rim around the cockpit.

307
00:18:17,297 --> 00:18:20,498
 they'll bond the frame in place
   later with a liquid plastic  

308
00:18:20,500 --> 00:18:23,234
       and adhesive putty.      

309
00:18:23,236 --> 00:18:26,237
    after priming the sanded    
   surface of the watercraft,   

310
00:18:26,239 --> 00:18:28,873
       team members lower       
    the 300-horsepower engine   

311
00:18:28,875 --> 00:18:30,275
         into the hatch.        

312
00:18:30,277 --> 00:18:34,411
  this is a dry fit to confirm  
 everything lines up correctly. 

313
00:18:34,413 --> 00:18:36,213
       they'll eventually       
        remove the engine       

314
00:18:36,215 --> 00:18:40,551
       for the final paint      
          and artwork.          

315
00:18:40,553 --> 00:18:43,621
    as the dry fit continues,   
   they connect the air tubes   

316
00:18:43,623 --> 00:18:46,824
       to the snorkel fins      
 that deliver air to the engine.

317
00:18:46,826 --> 00:18:54,098
                     ♪♪         

318
00:18:54,100 --> 00:18:57,035
  the engine hatch has, by now, 
        also been primed,       

319
00:18:57,037 --> 00:19:00,305
  and they fit it to the diving 
     watercraft's main body.    

320
00:19:00,307 --> 00:19:03,207
     the crew verifies that     
      the hatch sits flush      

321
00:19:03,209 --> 00:19:05,109
 with the rest of the fuselage. 

322
00:19:07,147 --> 00:19:09,813
  a worker installs the exhaust 
      outlet into the hole      

323
00:19:09,815 --> 00:19:13,317
 at the rear of the watercraft. 

324
00:19:13,319 --> 00:19:17,054
   crew members slide elevator  
 fins into bushings at the back.

325
00:19:17,056 --> 00:19:22,059
   these fins will control the  
  pitch axis of the watercraft. 

326
00:19:22,061 --> 00:19:24,996
       next, they install       
   the jet propulsion system.   

327
00:19:28,034 --> 00:19:29,367
      back to the cockpit,      

328
00:19:29,369 --> 00:19:32,370
   the crew bolts the control   
       pedals to the floor      

329
00:19:32,372 --> 00:19:34,839
         and run cables         
   to the jet propulsion unit,  

330
00:19:34,841 --> 00:19:37,175
       the elevator fins,       
    and the steering system.    

331
00:19:40,647 --> 00:19:42,880
         they reinstall         
     the dive fin scaffold,     

332
00:19:42,882 --> 00:19:45,249
  which has been powder coated  
       in a yellow color.       

333
00:19:48,021 --> 00:19:51,054
        the crew connects       
 the dive fins to the scaffold. 

334
00:19:51,056 --> 00:19:54,692
 they situate the control panel 
 just above the control pedals. 

335
00:19:57,163 --> 00:19:59,229
    they run a metal linkage    
       from the dive fins       

336
00:19:59,231 --> 00:20:01,699
       to a control stick.      

337
00:20:04,937 --> 00:20:07,971
they then test the control stick
      and confirm it moves      

338
00:20:07,973 --> 00:20:10,675
     the dive planes easily     
         and correctly.         

339
00:20:13,446 --> 00:20:16,280
        bucket seats made       
   of lightweight carbon fiber  

340
00:20:16,282 --> 00:20:18,516
        minimize the load       
        for added speed.        

341
00:20:21,320 --> 00:20:23,654
    they tuck a rubber gasket   
       into the framework       

342
00:20:23,656 --> 00:20:28,459
 for the clear canopy that will 
     surround the occupants.    

343
00:20:28,461 --> 00:20:29,660
   they add a bead of sealant   

344
00:20:29,662 --> 00:20:32,063
     where the gasket mates     
      to the window frame.      

345
00:20:34,300 --> 00:20:38,669
    the vessel canopy is made   
of thick aircraft-grade acrylic.

346
00:20:38,671 --> 00:20:41,205
        it's been tinted        
     to repel the sun's rays    

347
00:20:41,207 --> 00:20:45,242
 and keep the temperature cooler
         in the cockpit.        

348
00:20:45,244 --> 00:20:50,380
   the back canopy serves as a  
hatch for accessing the cockpit.

349
00:20:50,382 --> 00:20:53,184
       finally, an artist       
     does a custom paint job    

350
00:20:53,186 --> 00:20:55,620
     and makes the fuselage     
          look fierce.          

351
00:20:59,392 --> 00:21:01,793
       with the mechanical      
     components reinstalled,    

352
00:21:01,795 --> 00:21:06,663
     this diving watercraft     
   is ready to hit the water.   

353
00:21:06,665 --> 00:21:10,068
      fasten your seatbelt.     
   it should be quite a ride.   

